1 Preparing Data

This section is completely technical, so it may be omitted.

#Loading packages.
library(fintools)
library(xts)
library(vars)
library(ggplot2)
library(forecast)
library(MTS)
library(roll)
library(fDMA)
library(tseries)
library(gridExtra)
library(rugarch)
library(rmgarch)
#Importing data. 
tickers <-c("^GSPC", "TSLA")
data <- yahoo_quotes(tickers, 
                     origin = '2019-11-13')

names(data) <- c("Date","SP500", "TSLA")
#Calculating log-returns.
data <- cbind(data, logret(data, omit_na = F)[,2:3])
names(data) <- c("Date","SP500", "TSLA", "SP500_r", "TSLA_r")
#Formatting Date column.
data$Date <- as.Date(data$Date)
#Creating time series. 
sp500_ts <- ts(na.omit(data$SP500_r), start = c(2019, 220), frequency = 253)
tsla_ts <- ts(na.omit(data$TSLA_r), start = c(2019, 220), frequency = 253)
#Creating time series in xts fromat.
sp500_xts <- na.omit(xts(data$SP500_r, order.by = data$Date))
tsla_xts <- na.omit(xts(data$TSLA_r, order.by = data$Date))
whole <- na.omit(as.xts(cbind(data$SP500_r, data$TSLA_r), order.by = data$Date))
names(whole) <- c("SP500", "TSLA")

2 Preliminary Analysis

The data for the period of 11/13/2019 11/15/2020 is ready, so we can start working on it. First, lets plot quotes and log-returns. It is obvious that Tesla is more risky than the index. Tesla experienced at least two shocks, while the index only one. Also, the interquartile range of Tesla returns is wider.

#Plotting quotes and returns. 
plot1 <- ggplot(data)+
          geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = SP500))+
          labs(title = "SP500 Daily Quotes",
               y = "Value")
plot2 <- ggplot(data)+
          geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = TSLA))+
          labs(title = "TSLA Daily Quotes",
               y = "Value (in $)")
plot3 <- ggplot(na.omit(data))+
          geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = SP500_r))+
          labs(title = "SP500 Daily Log-Returns",
               y = "Returns")
plot4 <- ggplot(na.omit(data))+
          geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = TSLA_r))+
          labs(title = "TSLA Daily Log-Returns",
               y = "Returns")

grid.arrange(plot1, 
             plot2, 
             plot3,
             plot4,
             ncol=2)

##       Min.    1st Qu.     Median       Mean    3rd Qu.       Max.

##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max.

As we see in the plots below, data is not normally distributed, which is not something special. However, Tesla has thicker right tail, which means there are more excess positive returns, than negative, and S&P500 has thicker left tail, which means more excess negative returns, than positive.

plot5 <- ggplot(na.omit(data))+
          geom_density(aes(SP500_r), fill = "Grey")+
          labs(title = "Distribution of SP500 Retruns",
               x = "Returns")

plot6 <- ggplot(na.omit(data))+
          geom_density(aes(TSLA_r), fill = "Grey")+
          labs(title = "Distribution of TSLA Retruns",
               x = "Returns")

grid.arrange(plot5,
             plot6,
             nrow = 2)

Tests below confirm our conclusions.

#Testing normality of distribution of SP500 returns with Shapiro-Wilk test.
#H0: data normaly distributed;
#H1: data is not normaly distributied;
shapiro.test(sp500_ts)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sp500_ts
## W = 0.84055, p-value = 1.97e-15
#Testing normality of distribution of TSLA returns with Shapiro-Wilk test.
#H0: data normaly distributed;
#H1: data is not normaly distributied;
shapiro.test(tsla_ts)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  tsla_ts
## W = 0.93567, p-value = 4.627e-09

Correlation is not strong, only 50%. At this point, before proceeding to the study of ACFs, PACFs and CCFs, we can estimate a static beta for Tesla stock.

#Static CCM plot.
pairs(~ SP500_r + TSLA_r, data = na.omit(data), main = NA)

#Static CCM numerical.
cor(na.omit(data[,4:5]))

ACF and PACF of S&P500 show the presence of autocorrelations, while Telsa returns seem to be not autocorrelated.

#Plotting ACFs and PACFS.
par(mfrow = c(2,2) )
Acf(sp500_ts, lag.max = 20, main = "Series SP500")
Acf(tsla_ts, lag.max = 20, main = "Series TSLA")
Pacf(sp500_ts, lag.max = 20, main = "Series SP500")
Pacf(tsla_ts, lag.max = 20, main = "Series TSLA")

The hypothesis is confirmed by the Ljung-Box tests.

#Ljung-Box for detecting autocorrelations in SP500 returns.
#H0: all correlations are zero;
#H1: there exists at least one, which is significantly higher than zero;
Box.test(sp500_ts, lag = 30, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  sp500_ts
## X-squared = 223.81, df = 30, p-value < 2.2e-16
#Ljung-Box for detecting autocorrelations in TSLA returns.
#H0: all correlations are zero;
#H1: there exists at least one, which is significantly higher than zero;
Box.test(tsla_ts, lag = 30, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  tsla_ts
## X-squared = 30.647, df = 30, p-value = 0.4329

It is worth to underline, that SP&500 is a predictor, and Tesla is a response variable. There is some correlation at the lag 2, and weaker correlation at lag -2, which means Tesla returns respond more to S&P500 impulses at that lag, rather than vice versa.

#Plotting lagged ctoss-correlation function.
Ccf(data$SP500_r, data$TSLA_r, lag.max = 10, main = "SP500 & TSLA")

#ACF of squared SP500 series.
Acf(na.omit(sp500_ts)^2, lag.max = 20, main = "Series SP500")

The ACF plots of squared series of S&P500 and Tesla returns suggest, that the data is dependent and somewhat correlated in case of S&P500, and just dependent in case of Tesla, despite being weakly autocorrelated. Further ARCH testing shows the presence of ARCH effect in both cases.

#Testing ARCH effect in SP500 returns.
#H0: there is no ARCH effect;
#H1: there is ARCH effect with a specified lag;
archtest(as.vector(sp500_ts), lag = 2)
## 
##  Engle's LM ARCH Test
## 
## data:  as.vector(sp500_ts)
## statistic = 93.157, lag = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: ARCH effects of order 2 are present
archtest(as.vector(sp500_ts), lag = 5)
## 
##  Engle's LM ARCH Test
## 
## data:  as.vector(sp500_ts)
## statistic = 97.745, lag = 5, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: ARCH effects of order 5 are present
archtest(as.vector(sp500_ts), lag = 10)
## 
##  Engle's LM ARCH Test
## 
## data:  as.vector(sp500_ts)
## statistic = 104.71, lag = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: ARCH effects of order 10 are present
#ACF of squared TSLA series.
Acf(na.omit(tsla_ts)^2, lag.max = 20, main = "Series TSLA")

#Testing ARCH effect in TSLA returns.
#H0: there is no ARCH effect;
#H1: there is ARCH effect with a specified lag;
archtest(as.vector(tsla_ts), lag = 2)
## 
##  Engle's LM ARCH Test
## 
## data:  as.vector(tsla_ts)
## statistic = 17.391, lag = 2, p-value = 0.0001673
## alternative hypothesis: ARCH effects of order 2 are present
archtest(as.vector(tsla_ts), lag = 5)

The last impotant test is a stationarity test. In both cases the data follow a stationary process.

#Testing stationarity of SP500 returns.
#H0: non-stationary;
#H1: stationary;
adf.test(sp500_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  sp500_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -5.1471, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#Testing stationarity of TSLA returns.
#H0: non-stationary;
#H1: stationary;
adf.test(tsla_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  tsla_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.2497, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

3 ARMA Model For S&P500

For our DCC model we need to specify GARCH models for the series of returns. In another turn, for the GARCH model we should build mean models. After some trials and erros, the best specification is presented below. It is very helpful to look at PACF function of residuals in order to find the best specification for MA process. It allows to eliminate correlations in residuals.

#Building the ARMA model for SP500. 
sp500_arma <- arma(sp500_xts, order = c(0,2), list(ar = c(6,8), ma = c(1,2,9,7)))
## Warning in arma(sp500_xts, order = c(0, 2), list(ar = c(6, 8), ma = c(1, : order
## is ignored
summary(sp500_arma)

            "Fitted" = xts(sp500_arma$fitted.values, order.by = na.omit(data)$Date)),
     col = c("black", "red"),
     legend.loc = "topleft",
     main = "Fitted vs Observed, ARMA, SP500",
     lwd = c(2,2))

#Plotting PACF function of SP500 ARMA residuals. 
Pacf(sp500_arma$residuals, lag.max = 10, main = "SP500 Residuals")

In our case, the only problem is the distribution of residuals, which is not normal. It is well seen and also Shapiro-Wilk normality test rejects H0. Left tail is very fat, combining it with the plot of fitted values, we can conclude the model is bad in estimation of excess negative returns.

#Plotting the distribution of residuals.
ggplot(na.omit(data.frame("Residuals" = sp500_arma$residuals)))+
          geom_density(aes(Residuals), fill = "Grey")+
          labs(title = "Distribution of SP500 ARMA Residuals",
               x = "Residuals")

#Testing normality of distribution of SP500 ARMAA residuals with Shapiro-Wilk test.
#H0: data normaly distributed;
#H1: data is not normaly distributied;
shapiro.test(sp500_arma$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sp500_arma$residuals
## W = 0.89317, p-value = 4.009e-12

The PACF plot of squared residuals suggests to use alpha parameters with a lag no greater than two.

#Plotting PACF of squared SP500 ARMA residuals.
Pacf(sp500_arma$residuals^2, lag.max = 10, main = "Squared SP500 Residuals")

4 GARCH Model for S&P500

In this section we build a GARCH model for SP&500 series. We use the ARMA model from the previous section. GARCH order is chosen to be (1,1). We pick skewed student-t distribution for our model. The plot with results is presented below. The model is stable, since \((\alpha + \beta) < 1\).

#Building GARCH model for SP500. 
sp500_garch_spec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(8,9), include.mean = FALSE),
                                fixed.pars = list("ar1" = 0,
                                                  "ar2" = 0,
                                                  "ar3" = 0,
                                                  "ar4" = 0,
                                                  "ar5" = 0,
                                                  "ar6" = -0.1499937,
                                                  "ar7" = 0,
                                                  "ar8" = 0.0639182, 
                                                  "ma1" = 0.0607710,
                                                  "ma2" = 0.2443467,
                                                  "ma3" = 0,
                                                  "ma4" = 0,
                                                  "ma5" = 0,
                                                  "ma6" = 0,
                                                  "ma7" = 0.1600439,
                                                  "ma8" = 0,
                                                  "ma9" = 0.2540560),
                          variance.model = list(model = "sGARCH", garchOrder = c(1,1)),
                          distribution.model = "sstd")

sp500_garch <- ugarchfit(sp500_garch_spec, data = sp500_xts)
show(sp500_garch)

6 GARCH model for Tesla

The picture is similar to S&P500 GARCH model. The plot of results is below,

#Building GARCH model for TSLA. 
tsla_garch_spec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(2,2), include.mean = TRUE), 
                          variance.model = list(model = "sGARCH", garchOrder = c(1,1)),
                          distribution.model = "sstd")

tsla_garch <- ugarchfit(tsla_garch_spec, data = tsla_xts)

7 DCC Model For S&P500 And Tesla

In order to facilitate the process of building the DCC model, we can use HQ criterion and specify the max lag order, so the function dccfit would pick the VAR model with the lowest criterion. The built model uses multivariate student-t distribution.

#Building DCC model.
dcc.garch.spec <- dccspec(uspec = multispec(c(sp500_garch_spec, tsla_garch_spec)),
                           VAR = TRUE,
                           lag.max = 5,
                           lag.criterion = "HQ",
                           dccOrder = c(1,1), 
                           distribution = "mvt")


dcc.fit <- dccfit(dcc.garch.spec, data = whole)
dcc.fit

Now we can extract conditional standard deviations and correlations, as well as calculate rolling equivalents for comparison. The results are shown in the plot below.

#Calculating conditional standard deviations. 
cond.std <- sigma(dcc.fit)^0.5
#Calculating conditional correlations.
cond.cor <- rcor(dcc.fit)
cond.cor <- as.xts(cond.cor[1,2,], order.by = index(whole))
#Calculating rolling standard deviations.
roll.sd.sp500 <- roll_sd(sp500_xts, width = 20)
roll.sd.tsla <- roll_sd(tsla_xts, width = 20)
#Calculating rolling correlations.
roll.cor <- as.vector(roll_cor(sp500_xts, tsla_xts, width = 20))
#Plotting conditional correlations vs rolling correlations. 
plot(cbind("Conditional" = cond.cor,
           "Rolling" = roll.cor),
     col = c("black", "red"),
     legend.loc = "topleft",
     main = "Conditional vs Rolling Correlations",
     lwd = c(2,2))

8 Dynamic Conditional Betas And Its Alternatives

The final stage is a calculation of conditional dynamic and rolling betas. The final results are shown in the plot below. As we see, dynamic conditional betas seldom exceed the value of the static beta, while rolling betas are not stable. If we assume that conditional dynamic betas are more robust than rolling betas, then we can conclude that Tesla stock is either less volatile than the index or it is weakly correlated with it. We know for sure the last one is true, while the first one seems to be false, thus the reliability of the results can be justified to some degree.

#Calculating conditional betas. 
cond.beta <- cond.std[,2]/cond.std[,1] * cond.cor
names(cond.beta) <- c("Conditional")
#Calculating rolling betas.
roll.beta <- roll.cor * roll.sd.tsla /roll.sd.sp500
#Plotting betas.
plot(cbind("Conditional" = cond.beta,
           "Static" =  rep(tsla_beta$coefficients[2], length(cond.beta)),
           "Rolling" = roll.beta),
     col = c("black", "red", "green"),
     legend.loc = "topleft",
     main = "Conditional vs Rolling vs Static Betas",
     lwd = c(2,2))
